<h1>Restaurant-Style Lobster Corn Chowder</h1>
<p>A rich, creamy chowder that lets the sweetness of the lobster and fresh corn shine without becoming overly thick. Built in layers for a restaurant-quality result.</p>
<h2>Ingredients</h2>
<h3>Lobster</h3>
<ul>
<<<<<<< HEAD
  <li><span class="amount">2–3</span> <span class="item">lobster tails (or about 1½ lb cooked lobster meat)</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">2 tbsp</span> <span class="item">butter</span></li>
</ul>
<h3>Chowder</h3>
<ul>
  <li><span class="amount">4 slices</span> <span class="item">thick-cut bacon, diced</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">3 tbsp</span> <span class="item">butter</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1</span> <span class="item">medium onion, diced</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">2</span> <span class="item">celery stalks, diced</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1</span> <span class="item">medium carrot, finely diced</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">3 cloves</span> <span class="item">garlic, minced</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1/4 cup</span> <span class="item">all-purpose flour</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">4 cups</span> <span class="item">seafood stock (or chicken stock)</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">2 cups</span> <span class="item">whole milk</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1 cup</span> <span class="item">heavy cream</span></li>
  <li>1½ lb Yukon Gold potatoes, peeled and diced into ½-inch cubes</li>
  <li><span class="amount">4</span> <span class="item">ears fresh sweet corn, kernels removed (or 4 cups frozen corn)</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1</span> <span class="item">bay leaf</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1 tsp</span> <span class="item">fresh thyme leaves</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">1/2 tsp</span> <span class="item">smoked paprika</span></li>
  <li>Pinch of cayenne pepper (optional)</li>
  <li>Salt and freshly ground black pepper</li>
</ul>
<h3>Finish</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Reserved lobster meat</li>
  <li><span class="amount">1 tbsp</span> <span class="item">fresh lemon juice</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">2 tbsp</span> <span class="item">chopped fresh chives</span></li>
  <li><span class="amount">2 tbsp</span> <span class="item">chopped fresh parsley</span></li>
  <li>Reserved crispy bacon</li>
</ul>
<h2>Directions</h2>
<ol>
  <li>If using raw lobster tails, gently simmer them for 6–8 minutes until just cooked. Remove the meat from the shells, cut into bite-sized pieces, and reserve. Save the shells if making homemade lobster stock.</li>
  <li>In a large Dutch oven or heavy pot, cook the bacon until crisp. Remove the bacon and reserve for garnish, leaving about 2 tablespoons of bacon fat in the pot.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Add</span> the butter to the bacon fat. Add the onion, celery, and carrot and cook for 8–10 minutes until softened. Stir in the garlic and cook for 30 seconds.</li>
  <li>Sprinkle the flour over the vegetables and cook for about 2 minutes, stirring constantly.</li>
  <li>Slowly whisk in the seafood stock until smooth. Add the bay leaf, thyme, smoked paprika, and cayenne (if using). Bring to a gentle simmer.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Add</span> the diced potatoes and simmer for about 15 minutes, or until nearly tender.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Stir</span> in the milk and heavy cream. Do not allow the chowder to boil after adding the dairy.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Add</span> the corn and cook for another 5–8 minutes until tender but still slightly crisp.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Stir</span> in the lobster meat, lemon juice, and most of the bacon. Heat gently for 2–3 minutes, just until the lobster is warmed through.</li>
  <li><span class="verb">Remove</span> the bay leaf. Taste and season with salt and freshly ground black pepper.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Serving Suggestions</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Garnish with the remaining bacon, fresh chives, and parsley.</li>
  <li>Serve with oyster crackers, crusty sourdough, or a buttered grilled baguette.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Chef Tips</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Fresh summer corn produces the sweetest, most flavorful chowder.</li>
  <li>Yukon Gold potatoes provide a naturally creamy texture while holding their shape.</li>
  <li>Blend about 1 cup of the finished chowder and stir it back into the pot for a thicker, silkier consistency without making the entire soup smooth.</li>
  <li>If you have lobster shells available, simmer them in the seafood stock for 20–30 minutes before making the chowder for significantly deeper lobster flavor.</li>
  <li>A splash of dry sherry added after the vegetables have softened adds excellent depth.</li>
